Dmitri had the down payment stacked—$78,000 in a high-yield account, house hunt in full swing, three offers already under review. Then he saw the biotech run: FDA fast-track news dropped Friday evening, stock up 40% on Sunday pre-market. The options were priced stupidly, he said. “Volatility’s baked in, but the skew’s all wrong,” he told Ingrid over coffee. She asked if he was moving money from the house fund. He didn’t answer at first. Just smiled. “You know what Chidi made in ’23? On one trade. One. And he started with less than this.”  

Ingrid froze her creamer mid-pour. “That was gambling.”  

“No,” Dmitri said, “that was reading the board. Look—I keep half for the house. No changes. The other half? I’m not spreading it across ETFs to earn inflation plus two. I’m leveraging asymmetric upside on an event with a clear binary.”  

He walked her through it: defined risk, capped position size, the implied probability priced into the options far below what the trial data suggested. It wasn’t a moonshot. It was a calculated tilt. The trade made 3.8x in ten days. He doubled the down payment, kept half in cash, reinvested the rest conservatively. The house? Closed last month. White cabinets, open floor plan, view of the reservoir.  

“Everyone forgets,” Dmitri said later, “that caution compounds too. Only it compounds poverty.”  

Ingrid still won’t touch options. But she asked him to review her portfolio.

