------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Dmitri called Noor at 11:47 p.m. after the biotech stock he’d bought on margin jumped 40 percent in after-hours. He wasn’t celebrating—he was panicking. “Is this real? Can it go back down by tomorrow?” Noor said, “Yes, and yes.” She wasn’t being cold. She was the one who’d told him, six weeks earlier, “If you’ve got dry powder and a pulse, and you actually believe in something, don’t dribble it in. Go in heavy.”

He had $58,000 saved from two years at a fintech startup—post-tax, no debt, rent covered for nine months. He put $42,000 into a small biotech play poised to hit Phase 3 results soon. Half of that on margin. Classic beginner move, people say. Reckless. Emotional. But let’s be real: if you’re not willing to feel sick to your stomach once in a while, you’re donating years of potential upside to the people who are.

The issue wasn’t the margin. It was that no one around him could tell the difference between gambling and conviction. His coworker Felix pulled him aside the next morning, said, “Dude, you’re one red day from a margin call.” As if Felix had ever held anything more volatile than a 529 plan.

Look—margin’s a tool. It’s not for everyone. But if you can afford to lose the money and you’ve done the work—if you’re not just chasing a meme or reacting to a newsletter headline—then why pretend humility is the default smart move? Indexing your whole life is discipline on autopilot. Fine for people who need it. But Dmitri wasn’t one of them.

Noor told him to set a stop at 25 percent below entry, not because the stock would collapse, but because even good bets deserve risk parameters. Know your exit before you’re breathless watching the ticker. She also said: “If you’re leveraging, at least make sure it’s not your only bet. But if it’s your only idea? Then bet like you mean it.”

He sold a third at 40 percent gain, enough to cover the margin loan and then some. Held the rest. The stock dropped two days later on investor skepticism, but the trial data was solid. It climbed back.

Felix still won’t touch anything outside an ETF. Dmitri’s second bet is on a cryptocurrency play—smaller size, same approach. He’s setting up alerts now. Noor keeps telling him to watch funding rates, but he thinks she’s overcomplicating it.

