Owen tells this story like it’s a guilty secret. But I don’t think he should.

Back when that small biotech stock started moonshotting? The one with the experimental treatment? He was in a bad job, barely saving, watching the market and thinking, “I’m either gonna be rich or I’m gonna learn.”

He tapped his retirement. Not the whole thing — but enough. Threw it in while the thing was still under five bucks. People lost their minds. “You’re nuking your 401k!” like he’d committed financial heresy.

But here’s what they didn’t see. Owen had family money — not a trust fund, but enough that if this blew up, he’d be okay. He wasn’t betting the farm. He was testing a thesis.

And the rally wasn’t random. Volume was spiking. Insiders were buying. Every dip got bought hard. It felt like being the only one awake at 3 a.m.

He tripled his money in eight weeks. Cashed half out, rode the rest down, then sideways. Still came out ahead.

The thing everyone misses? That window only stays open for hot stocks like that for, what, a month? Maybe two? If you wait for permission, you miss it.

So yeah, cashing out early is “risky.” But doing nothing while everything moves without you — that’s the real cost.

Anyway. Last I heard, Owen’s looking at a new cryptocurrency. Says it’s got the same energy.
